chunk_content: • Clients who present for testing as the result of receiving a social network testing coupon or 89 referral, but who identify as being a sexual and/or needle-sharing partner with an individual known to be living with HIV should be counted under HTS_INDEX and not under the HTS_TST SNS modality. T E S Please refer to HTS_TST for information on Data Quality and reporting considerations that would T also apply here. I N G Key Populations: Provision of data (on any of the steps outlined above) specific to key populations (FSW, MSM, transgender people, PWID, and people in prisons and other closed settings) who were tested and received their results should be included but not disaggregated into a separate ‘KP’ disaggregate. That is, there is no separate Key Population disaggregate requested for HTS_INDEX (unlike HTS_TST). The first priority of data collection and reporting of testing for the index client and their contacts, particularly key populations, must be to do no harm.
